export const title = "Advanced";
export const description = "Custom fonts, animation, and dynamic font loading for React Native Vector Icons";
export const body = "Custom icon fonts, animation, and dynamic font loading.\n\n## Custom Fonts\n\nThe best approach is to use the icon generator to create your own icon package. See the [Creating a Font Package](./custom-fonts) guide to learn how.\n\nYou can also use `createIconSet()` directly in your project. This returns a custom icon component based on a `glyphMap` where the key is the icon name and the value is either a UTF-8 character or its character code.\n\n`postScriptName` is the name of the PostScript font. Open the font in [fontdrop.info](https://fontdrop.info/), Font Book.app, or similar to learn the name. Also pass the `fontFileName` argument for Android support.\n\n```js\nimport { createIconSet } from \"@react-native-vector-icons/common\";\n\nconst glyphMap = { \"icon-name\": 1234, test: \"∆\" };\n\nconst Icon = createIconSet(glyphMap, {\n  postScriptName: \"FontName\",\n  fontFileName: \"font-name.ttf\",\n  fontSource: require(\"../fonts/font-name.ttf\"), // optional, for dynamic loading\n});\n```\n\n> [!TIP]\n> If you are not using dynamic font loading, make sure your font is copied into your app bundle.\n\n### Type-checked Icon Names\n\nPass a union of icon names as a generic parameter to `createIconSet` to get type-checking and autocomplete on the `name` prop. This is most useful when you supply your own glyphmap (Fontello, IcoMoon, or a custom font) — the bundled icon packages already export typed components.\n\n```tsx\nimport { createIconSet } from \"@react-native-vector-icons/common\";\n\nconst Icon = createIconSet<\"home\" | \"settings\" | \"user\">(glyphMap, {\n  postScriptName: \"FontName\",\n  fontFileName: \"font-name.ttf\",\n});\n\n<Icon name=\"home\" />     // ok\n<Icon name=\"invalid\" />  // type error\n```\n\n## Animation\n\nReact Native ships with [Animated](https://reactnative.dev/docs/animated.html), a powerful animation library. To animate an icon, create an animated component:\n\n```js\nconst AnimatedIcon = Animated.createAnimatedComponent(Icon);\n```\n\nYou can also use the higher-level animation library [react-native-animatable](https://github.com/oblador/react-native-animatable).\n\n## Dynamic Font Loading\n\nFonts can be available in an app **statically** (since build time) or loaded **dynamically** at runtime. Dynamic loading is useful for apps that use over-the-air updates and want to load new fonts with an update, or when you need to use a font from a remote location.\n\n> [!TIP]\n> **Platform Support** — Dynamic loading is supported on all platforms if you use Expo ([Expo Go](https://expo.dev/go) or a [development build](https://docs.expo.dev/develop/development-builds/introduction/)). In future, it should become available for all React Native projects via React Native core.\n\n### Static vs Dynamic Imports\n\nIf you do not need dynamic loading, use the `/static` imports (e.g. `@react-native-vector-icons/ionicons/static`) for a smaller bundle.\n\nBy default, dynamic loading is enabled if you run Expo SDK ≥ 52. It does not change the way you work with the package: if rendering an icon requires a font that is not known to the app, it will be loaded automatically and the icon will render as expected.\n\n> [!WARNING]\n> **Limitation** — Dynamic loading in `@react-native-vector-icons` is currently limited to fonts bundled within the provided packages. It does not support Pro fonts (such as FontAwesome Pro). However, you can use `createIconSet` with a `fontSource` to enable dynamic loading for custom fonts.\n\n### API Functions\n\n`@react-native-vector-icons/common` exports several functions to control dynamic loading:\n\n| Function | Description |\n| --- | --- |\n| `isDynamicLoadingEnabled` | Returns whether dynamic loading is enabled. |\n| `isDynamicLoadingSupported` | Returns whether dynamic loading is supported by your runtime (checks that the necessary Expo features are present). |\n| `setDynamicLoadingEnabled` | Enables or disables dynamic loading. |\n| `setDynamicLoadingErrorCallback` | Sets a callback invoked when an error occurs during dynamic loading (e.g. a misconfigured OTA update missing a font file). |";
